      "content": "Ah, my apologies for the goblin reference. I meant to say \"quirks\" instead. Regarding your Monstera, if the soil feels damp even without recent watering, it might indeed be overwatering. Overwatering can lead to root rot, which can cause the yellowing and brown spots you're seeing. However, it's also possible that pests or a fungal infection could be the culprits. Check the undersides of the leaves for any signs of pests, like tiny insects or webs, and look for any unusual spots or patterns that might indicate a fungal issue. If you find anything, you might need to treat the plant accordingly. Remember, plants can be quite the tricksters, but with a little attention, you'll have them back to their mischievous self in no time!",
