      "content": "If you discover root rot, don't worry, there's hope for your Monstera. The first step is to remove it from its current pot to inspect the roots. Healthy roots should be white and firm, while root rot will appear brown and mushy. Trim away any rotten roots with sterilized scissors or pruning shears. Then, give your plant a fresh pot with well-draining soil – a mix designed for tropical plants is a good choice. Water it sparingly until it shows signs of recovery, and keep it in a spot with bright, indirect light. Patience is key, and with some tender care, your Monstera can bounce back from this ordeal. Just remember, even the most stubborn goblin can be tamed with a bit of persistence and the right approach!",
